Introduction
 work in the field of molecular cell biology and the projects of our laboratory are distant from pharmacology and toxicology. herefore, instead of showing you results from some work originating from our laboratory (see kindly β€�http://lge.lf1.cuni.czβ€�),  shall tell you a story of the utchison-ilford progeria syndrome () that explicitly documents the importance of molecular cell biology investigations in human medicine. n order to fulfill this aim simply,  explain here the results of only a few of the relevant experiments that are directly linked to the  story.
he  is one type of laminopathies, alternatively called the nuclear envelope diseases. ost cases of  result from a nucleotide position 1824 β†’  mutation (substitution mutation from cytosine to thymine) in the gene coding lamin  () that creates an ectopic m. RNA splicing site leading to an expression of truncated prelamin A. If compared to β€�normalβ€� prelamin A protein, truncated prelamin A lacks 50 amino acids within its tail domain. Both normal and truncated prelamin A proteins are subjects to extensive post-translational modifications (PTMs). The PTMs play an important role in the HGPS story.
Generally speaking, it should be noted here that the causes of many human diseases are due to an incorrect splicing of various precursor mRNAs.
