Posttranslational modifications of prelamin  and progerin
essenger  for lamin  is translated, giving rise to the precursor protein β€�prelamin ,β€� which is subject to extensive s. ne of the modifications is addition of a farnesyl group to prelamin . t the -end of normal (as well as progeric) prelamin , the polypeptide chain has a special sequence of 4 amino acids, cysteine-serine-isoleucine-methionine () sequence. his sequence, termed generally a β€� boxβ€�, is the target site of an enzyme β€“ farnesyl transferase (ase). he enzyme adds to the cysteine of the  sequence a lipophilic farnesyl group. ysteine farnelysation results in the association of prelamin  as well as progerin with the (lipophilic) . t should be noted that farnesylation of proteins is a common feature of numerous proteins containing  box sequences (e.g., as protein is farnesylated).
n the cell, still other modifications of prelamin  take place. or example, the sequence  is cleaved away and is replaced by carboxymethylation of cysteine. owever, the important modification for  is that the terminal sequence in prelamin  is cleaved by the endoprotease mpste24. his protease cleaves off the end of the prelamin  sequence, including the farnesylated cysteine, and gives rise to mature lamin  protein. amin  is thus no longer targeted to the . mportantly, this cleavage cannot take place in the progerin molecule as the endoprotease needs the missing 50 amino acids to perform the cleavage job. s the results, progerin remains anchored to the  and accumulates there.
n summary, farnesylation of progerin has a deleterious effect on the diseased cell.nd importantly,  documented here how molecular cell biology helped to discover the basic mechanism behind the .Posttranslational modifications of prelamin A and progerin
Messenger RNA for lamin A is translated, giving rise to the precursor protein β€�prelamin A,β€� which is subject to extensive PTMs. One of the modifications is addition of a farnesyl group to prelamin A. At the C-end of normal (as well as progeric) prelamin A, the polypeptide chain has a special sequence of 4 amino acids, cysteine-serine-isoleucine-methionine (CSIM) sequence. This sequence, termed generally a β€�CAAX boxβ€�, is the target site of an enzyme β€“ farnesyl transferase (FTase). The enzyme adds to the cysteine of the CSIM sequence a lipophilic farnesyl group. Cysteine farnelysation results in the association of prelamin A as well as progerin with the (lipophilic) INM. It should be noted that farnesylation of proteins is a common feature of numerous proteins containing CAAX box sequences (e.g., Ras protein is farnesylated).
In the cell, still other modifications of prelamin A take place. For example, the sequence SIM is cleaved away and is replaced by carboxymethylation of cysteine. However, the important modification for HGPS is that the terminal sequence in prelamin A is cleaved by the endoprotease Zmpste24. This protease cleaves off the end of the prelamin A sequence, including the farnesylated cysteine, and gives rise to mature lamin A protein. Lamin A is thus no longer targeted to the INM. Importantly, this cleavage cannot take place in the progerin molecule as the endoprotease needs the missing 50 amino acids to perform the cleavage job. As the results, progerin remains anchored to the INM and accumulates there.
In summary, farnesylation of progerin has a deleterious effect on the diseased cell.And importantly, I documented here how molecular cell biology helped to discover the basic mechanism behind the HGPS.
